You hit the nail on the head—getting both of your cameras onto one website at the same time from two different locations is the trickiest part of this project.

To make this work, you need a technology called WebRTC (Web Real-Time Communication), which allows two browsers to stream video directly to each other. The easiest way to pull this off without paying for complicated servers is by using a free JavaScript library called PeerJS.

Here is exactly how the whole system will work and what you need to build:
The Game Plan

We can break your project down into two main pages.

Page 1: The Greeting

    The Look: A light pastel background (like baby pink or white).

    The Animation: We'll use a CSS animation library to make hearts float up from the bottom of the screen.

    The Text: "Happy 1st monthsary season 2" right in the center.

    The Button: Positioned at the bottom right, saying "You wanna see your gift?", which links to the photobooth page.

Page 2: The Shared Photobooth
This is where the magic happens. When you both open this second page, the website will ask for camera permissions.

    The site generates a unique "Room ID" for you.

    You send that ID to your girlfriend (or she clicks a specific link).

    PeerJS connects your browsers. Her video feed pops up next to yours on the screen.

    When you click "Capture," the website uses the HTML Canvas API to instantly stitch both of your video feeds into a single downloadable image.

How to actually build it

Since you want to host on Vercel, the best tool for the job is Next.js (a React framework). Vercel built Next.js, so they work together perfectly.

1
Initialize the project
Requires Node.js installed on your computer

Open your computer's terminal and run npx create-next-app@latest monthsary-booth. This sets up the skeleton of your website.
2
Build the Greeting Page

In the main page file, you'll add the light background, write the greeting text, and add the "See your gift" button. You can use a library like react-confetti or simple CSS for the floating hearts.
3
Set up PeerJS for the Cameras

You'll install PeerJS (npm install peerjs). You will write a script that says: "Grab my local webcam, then call the other person's ID and grab their webcam, and put them side-by-side."
4
Create the Capture Button

You will create a hidden HTML <canvas>. When the capture button is clicked, the code will draw Video 1 on the left side of the canvas, Video 2 on the right side, and then export that canvas as a .png file.
5
Deploy to Vercel

Push your code to GitHub, log into Vercel, and click "Import Project." It will give you a live URL you can send to your girlfriend.

This is a really fun project, but handling webcams and peer-to-peer connections can be a bit heavy if you haven't done it before.

